deck: An 26-issue bi-weekly miniseries featuring the former members of Justice League International and the schemes of the resurrected Maxwell Lord.
description:
Justice League: Generation Lost is a bi-weekly title written by Judd Winick and drawn by a rotating team of artists which was first published in 2010. The book forms part of DC's multi-title Brightest Day event, with the title focusing on the fall-out of Maxwell Lord's resurrection during the events of Geoff John's Blackest Night arc.

The lead characters in Generation Lost include stalwarts of the former Justice League International - including Booster Gold, Captain Atom, Fire and Ice - whilst incorporating a new Red Rocket and Blue Beetle, Jaime Reyes. The story commences with a huge manhunt for Max Lord before it is revealed that he has amplified his mind control abilities with the use of a machine, with the result being that only the aforementioned heroes can recall his existence and past crimes. They reconvene with the goal of capturing Lord and ending his elaborate mind-wipe.

This series is also collected into two hardcovers:

  • Justice League: Generation Lost Vol. 1 (#1-12)
  • Justice League: Generation Lost Vol. 2 (#13-24)
name: Justice League: Generation Lost

The Sixth Gun is a post American Civil War story of ancient weapons and supernatural occurrence. "The Six" show up in all forms across the world and its history but their true power and purpose is shrouded in deep Cajun style mystery of this book. In search of money and treasure Drake Sinclair navigates with an unmeasured knowledge of Southern magic until he is reunited with his former acquaintances looking to revive a crazed war veteran, General Hume. Hume and his men carry the estranged "six" in the form of special revolvers, each with its own specific ability. They can raise the dead, predict the future, and grant other unimaginable power. Completely unaware of the world she is about to be thrown into Becky Montcrief mourns the murder of her grandfather and acquires General Hume's piece of "the six". Drake and Becky's journey will attract demons, mysterious magicians, and bloodthirsty immortals in this Oni Press hit title. Cullen Bunn and Brian Hurtt present to you, "The Sixth Gun".

deck: Symbolizing the fear and discovery of traveling to a new land, this wordless graphic novel tells the tale of an immigrant who starts a new life in a fantastic new land.
description:
The Arrival by Shaun Tan is the story of an immigrant told through a series of wordless images that emulate the style of a 1930's Depression-era photograph. A man is forced to leave his wife and child in an impoverished town in order to seek better prospects in an unknown country on the other side of a vast ocean. The story follows the man's experiences and struggles as he eventually finds himself in a bewildering city of foreign customs, strange animals, odd floating objects, and incomprehensible languages. These fantastical aspects allow the reader to truly connect with the character's isolation, not to mention the many other feelings that are brought about by this change. 
  
The Arrival has so far won the "Book of the Year" prize as part of the New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards in 2006, as well as the Children's Book Council of Australia "Picture Book of the Year" award in 2007.
name: The Arrival

Where does THE PUNISHER fit into Clarke's plans? It's the end of the world as we know it- time to cross some names off the old enemies list.
